				\begin{document}$${R2}_{3 T}^{*}=2.051 {R2}_{1.5 T}^{*}-25.4276$$\end{document}R23T∗=2.051R21.5T∗-25.4276

Direct conversion from 3 T-R2* to LIC is also possible using d’Assignies’ calibration curve [7]. In their paper, d’Assignies’ et al. give two equations, one of which was for patients with LIC of < 7.26 mg/g dw. We chose this equation for our study as it was the more relevant to the LIC range for the population we examined. The d’Assignies equation is given in their paper in μmol/g dw, so this was converted to mg/g dw using the atomic weight of iron. The d’Assignies equation becomes:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
